Document: Customizing HTML5 Shell
Path: godot/tutorials/platform/web/customizing_html5_shell.rst
Summary: This document explains how to customize the HTML5 shell for Godot projects.

This tutorial covers how to customize the HTML5 shell for your Godot projects. This allows you to change the appearance and behavior of the web export of your game.

You can find the default HTML5 shell files in the `misc/web/` directory of the Godot Engine source code. To customize it, you should copy these files to your project directory and modify them.

**Key Files:**

*   `index.html`: The main HTML file for your game. You can modify the `<head>` and `<body>` sections to include custom CSS, JavaScript, or meta tags.
*   `godot.js`: The JavaScript file that runs your Godot game. You can modify this file to hook into game events or change runtime behavior, but this is generally not recommended unless you know what you are doing.
*   `godot.wasm`: The WebAssembly binary for your game. This file should not be modified.
*   `style.css`: A basic CSS file for styling the page. You can add your own styles here.

**Customization Steps:**

1.  **Copy Default Files:** Copy the contents of `misc/web/` from the Godot source code to a new folder in your project, for example, `web/`.
2.  **Modify `index.html`:**
    *   Add custom CSS links or `<style>` tags in the `<head>` section.
    *   Add custom HTML elements or content in the `<body>` section.
    *   You can change the title of the page, add meta descriptions, etc.
3.  **Modify `style.css`:** Add your own CSS rules to style the game container, loading screen, or any other elements you add to `index.html`.
4.  **Export Your Project:** When exporting your project for the web, set the "Export Path" to the `web/` folder you created. Godot will then use your customized shell files.

**Example: Adding a custom loading screen:**

In `index.html`, you can add a loading screen element:

```html
<div id="loading-screen">
    <img src="loading.gif" alt="Loading...">
</div>
```

Then, in `style.css`, style it:

```css
#loading-screen {
    position: absolute;
    top: 0;
    left: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    background-color: black;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    z-index: 9999;
}
```

You would also need to add a `loading.gif` file to your `web/` folder.

**Important Considerations:**

*   **Browser Compatibility:** Ensure your customizations are compatible with the target browsers.
*   **Performance:** Avoid overly complex or resource-intensive customizations that could impact game performance.
*   **Updates:** When updating Godot, you may need to re-copy and re-apply your customizations to the new default shell files.

By following these steps, you can create a unique and branded experience for your Godot games on the web.
